  "prompt": "Why are there two capital letters in the surname McCall?",
  "response": "The surname McCall has two capital letters because it is a compound name derived from the Scottish and Irish tradition. The \"Mc\" part is an abbreviation of the Gaelic word \"Mac,\" which means \"son of.\" The second capital letter represents the start of the father's name or another significant name that follows the \"Mc\" prefix. In this case, \"Call\" is likely derived from a personal name, such as \"Callum\" or \"Cailin.\" Therefore, the two capital letters in McCall signify the joining of these two elements to form a complete surname.",
